---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Least Privilege & Security Boundaries — AI Agent Puzzle"
  description="After connecting an MCP, the next important question is: should it be allowed to do everything? This page uses Gemini CLI's includeTools and excludeTools settings to shrink the tool surface down to the minimum set your task actually needs."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container ai-agent-security">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Don't Let AI Do Too Much Just Yet</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          What we did earlier was important: you got Gemini CLI connected to Notion and actually ran through a full workflow, so you know AI can help you search pages, read content, create new pages, and even update pages. What you'll learn here is the next, more important question.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Just because it can, should I let it do everything?<br/>
          <strong>My answer: not yet.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        "It works" is only step one. What matters more is "<strong>it works safely</strong>." The goal of this page is to help you start a habit: <strong>more tools aren't better — open only the few that the task actually needs</strong>. Gemini CLI's MCP configuration itself supports <code>includeTools</code> and <code>excludeTools</code> for tool filtering; and if the same tool is both allowed and excluded, <code>excludeTools</code> wins.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Why "it works" isn't enough -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Why "It Works" Isn't Enough</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The first time you hook AI up to tools, it's exciting, and a natural thought pops up:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example">
        Since it's connected, wouldn't it be easiest to just open everything to it?
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        On the surface this sounds reasonable, but in practice it usually makes things easier to spiral out of control. When an agent can touch too many tools and take too many actions, <strong>its capabilities grow — and so does the blast radius when it gets something wrong</strong>.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You can think of it simply. If all you want is for it to:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Find pages related to a topic</li>
        <li>Pull out the key points</li>
        <li>Build a draft</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        then it doesn't necessarily need to update pages, change statuses, or modify a bunch of existing content. Extra capabilities <strong>look like convenience but usually just add another layer of risk</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          The mature approach isn't turning everything on at once — it's <strong>limiting capability to the minimum set the task actually needs</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: What is minimum privilege -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">What "Least Privilege" Means</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You can start by understanding "least privilege" as one plain sentence:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          <strong>Give it only the capabilities needed for the task at hand — no more.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This idea actually applies beyond AI — it applies to many system settings. It just becomes more important once we're talking about an AI agent, because <strong>an agent isn't just a button — it decides on its own which tool to use next</strong>.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In Gemini CLI's MCP config:
      </p>

      <div class="concept-grid">
        <article class="concept-card">
          <p class="concept-tag">Whitelist</p>
          <h3 class="concept-title"><code>includeTools</code></h3>
          <p class="concept-desc">
            "<strong>Only these tools are allowed</strong>." If you don't set <code>includeTools</code>, every tool the server exposes is open by default.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="concept-card">
          <p class="concept-tag">Blacklist</p>
          <h3 class="concept-title"><code>excludeTools</code></h3>
          <p class="concept-desc">
            "<strong>Turn these tools off</strong>." If a tool is in both <code>includeTools</code> and <code>excludeTools</code>, exclude wins.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So the core of this page isn't memorizing a bunch of security terms. It's about slowly building a habit of asking yourself:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>For this specific task, which tools do I <strong>actually need</strong>?</li>
        <li>Which ones <strong>shouldn't be open yet</strong>?</li>
        <li>Which ones can wait <strong>until I'm more familiar</strong>?</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Section: How to narrow tools in Gemini CLI -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">How to Shrink the Tool Surface in Gemini CLI</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Continuing with the Notion route, the first time you do a safety config, I recommend trimming the tool list down to these 3 and turning update off for now:
      </p>

      <ul class="permission-list">
        <li class="permission-item permission-item--on">
          <span class="permission-icon">✓</span>
          <div class="permission-body">
            <p class="permission-name"><code>notion-search</code></p>
            <p class="permission-desc">Search pages</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="permission-item permission-item--on">
          <span class="permission-icon">✓</span>
          <div class="permission-body">
            <p class="permission-name"><code>notion-fetch</code></p>
            <p class="permission-desc">Read pages</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="permission-item permission-item--on">
          <span class="permission-icon">✓</span>
          <div class="permission-body">
            <p class="permission-name"><code>notion-create-pages</code></p>
            <p class="permission-desc">Create pages</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="permission-item permission-item--off">
          <span class="permission-icon">✗</span>
          <div class="permission-body">
            <p class="permission-name"><code>notion-update-page</code></p>
            <p class="permission-desc">Update pages (turn off for now)</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The reason is simple. For beginners, <strong>"search, read, create draft" is already enough to finish a lot of useful work</strong>, and the risk is much lower than "update existing pages." Update isn't off limits forever — it just belongs in a later step, once you really know how AI tends to act.
      </p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Where does the config file live?</h3>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Gemini CLI's config file has two common locations, and <strong>project-level settings override user-level</strong>:
      </p>

      <div class="scope-grid">
        <article class="scope-card">
          <p class="scope-card__label">User level</p>
          <p class="scope-card__path"><code>~/.gemini/settings.json</code></p>
          <p class="scope-card__desc">
            Applies to every project on your machine.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="scope-card">
          <p class="scope-card__label">Project level</p>
          <p class="scope-card__path"><code>.gemini/settings.json</code></p>
          <p class="scope-card__desc">
            Applies only to the current folder.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          I suggest starting with the <strong>project-level</strong> <code>.gemini/settings.json</code>. It's safer to practice on a small scope first, rather than applying a rule across every project from day one.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">How to find it</h3>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Follow this path to the config file:
      </p>
      <nav class="path-breadcrumb" aria-label="settings.json path">
        <span class="path-step">C: drive</span>
        <span class="path-sep">→</span>
        <span class="path-step">Users</span>
        <span class="path-sep">→</span>
        <span class="path-step">&lt;username&gt;</span>
        <span class="path-sep">→</span>
        <span class="path-step">.gemini</span>
        <span class="path-sep">→</span>
        <span class="path-step path-step--file">settings.json</span>
      </nav>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Method 1: Whitelist (includeTools)</h3>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You can change the Notion server to:
      </p>
      <pre class="code-block code-block--json"><code>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "notion": {
      "httpUrl": "https://mcp.notion.com/mcp",
      "includeTools": [
        "notion-search",
        "notion-fetch",
        "notion-create-pages"
      ]
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          The meaning of this config is straightforward: <strong>I'm only letting this server provide search, read, and create-page capabilities.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Save and try it out</h3>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Save → restart Gemini CLI → send these 4 prompts in order:
      </p>

      <ol class="test-list">
        <li class="test-item">
          <span class="test-num">1</span>
          <div class="test-body">
            <p class="test-desc">Please search Notion for pages related to "final report" and list the 3 most relevant — don't modify anything.</p>
            <p class="test-tag test-tag--ok">Works</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="test-item">
          <span class="test-num">2</span>
          <div class="test-body">
            <p class="test-desc">Please open the most relevant page from earlier and summarize the points related to the final report requirements.</p>
            <p class="test-tag test-tag--ok">Works</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="test-item">
          <span class="test-num">3</span>
          <div class="test-body">
            <p class="test-desc">Based on those points, please create a new Notion page titled "Final Report Key Points" — present it as a bullet list first.</p>
            <p class="test-tag test-tag--ok">Works</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="test-item test-item--blocked">
          <span class="test-num">4</span>
          <div class="test-body">
            <p class="test-desc">Please update the page you just created: add a short summary at the top and organize the content under three subheadings.</p>
            <p class="test-tag test-tag--blocked">Blocked</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The strength of Notion MCP isn't any single step — it's <strong>chaining these tools together</strong>. The first 3 steps still work, but step 4 "update page" is no longer an available capability.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Blacklist alternative -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">If You Don't Want a Whitelist, Start with a Blacklist</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Some people feel that listing a whitelist up front is a hassle, because you have to know all the tool names first. Another easier-to-grasp approach is to <strong>just turn off the tool you least want it to touch — "update page"</strong>:
      </p>

      <pre class="code-block code-block--json"><code>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "notion": {
      "httpUrl": "https://mcp.notion.com/mcp",
      "excludeTools": [
        "notion-update-page"
      ]
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The upside of this style is that it reads very plainly:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Don't modify existing pages</li>
        <li>Keep search, read, and draft creation</li>
        <li>Unlock update once you're more comfortable</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Section: When to use which -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">When to Use includeTools vs excludeTools</h2>

      <div class="when-grid">
        <article class="when-card when-card--primary">
          <p class="when-card__label">First time using a tool</p>
          <h3 class="when-card__title">Use <code>includeTools</code></h3>
          <p class="when-card__quote">"Only open the few I know I'll use."</p>
          <p class="when-card__desc">The boundary is the clearest this way.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="when-card">
          <p class="when-card__label">After a few runs already</p>
          <h3 class="when-card__title">Use <code>excludeTools</code></h3>
          <p class="when-card__quote">"Leave the rest as-is, just not these few."</p>
          <p class="when-card__desc">Best when you only want to temporarily disable a few high-risk actions.</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          Both approaches work. The difference isn't about technique — it's whether you're at the "<strong>just starting</strong>" or "<strong>somewhat experienced</strong>" stage.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Fully open (danger) -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">The Riskiest Version: Wide Open</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If you connect the Notion MCP and <strong>don't add any tool restriction</strong>, then whatever tools the server exposes, Gemini CLI can see and use them all by default.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          This is why "connected" and "safe" are two different things: <strong>connecting only establishes the link — safety depends on whether you added a boundary</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Wide-open access feels great the first time, because everything is testable. But it's also the most likely to lead to situations like:
      </p>
      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>You wanted it to just find info, but it starts wanting to do more</li>
        <li>You wanted it to just read content, but it has the ability to modify content directly</li>
        <li>You wanted it to just draft something, but it might touch pages you didn't want it to</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The simplest form of the wide-open version in your <code>.gemini/settings.json</code> looks like this:
      </p>
      <pre class="code-block code-block--json"><code>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "notion": {
      "httpUrl": "https://mcp.notion.com/mcp"
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

      <!-- Section: Common errors -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Common Errors and Misconceptions</h2>

      <ol class="mistake-list">
        <li class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-num">1</span>
          <div class="mistake-body">
            <h3 class="mistake-title">Errors when editing <code>.gemini/settings.json</code></h3>
            <p class="mistake-desc">
              If you add only <code>includeTools</code> or <code>excludeTools</code>, <strong>remember to put a comma at the end of the previous line</strong>. JSON is strict about commas — one missing and the whole file won't parse.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-num">2</span>
          <div class="mistake-body">
            <h3 class="mistake-title">"If I just write careful prompts, I don't need tool restrictions"</h3>
            <p class="mistake-desc mistake-desc--caution">
              Not quite. Because <strong>no matter how careful your prompt is, it doesn't mean you actually added a boundary to the system</strong>. Tool restrictions build a "<strong>structural boundary</strong>" — not a "hope for the best."
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .ai-agent-security {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Sub-heading inside a section */
  .sub-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    padding-left: var(--space-3);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
  }

  /* Inline code */
  :global(.detail-paragraph) code,
  :global(.detail-subtitle) code,
  :global(.check-list) code,
  :global(.cross-list) code,
  :global(.callout-text) code,
  :global(.highlight-text) code,
  :global(.scope-card__desc) code,
  :global(.mistake-title) code,
  :global(.mistake-desc) code {
    padding: 0.1em 0.4em;
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-tag-text);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  /* Code block (JSON) */
  .code-block {
    margin: var(--space-3) 0;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-8);
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    line-height: 1.7;
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    overflow-x: auto;
    white-space: pre;
    color: var(--color-heading);
  }

  .code-block code {
    padding: 0;
    background: none;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-size: inherit;
  }

  /* Check list */
  .check-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .check-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .check-list li::before {
    content: '\2713';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .check-list li strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Cross list (✗ items) */
  .cross-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .cross-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.9;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .cross-list li::before {
    content: '\2717';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* Callout card */
  .callout-card {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-8);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
  }

  .callout-text {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .callout-text strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Highlight card (key takeaway) */
  .highlight-card {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .highlight-text {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-heading);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin: 0;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .highlight-text strong {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* Prompt example (quote-style) */
  .prompt-example {
    margin: var(--space-3) 0;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-radius: 0 var(--border-radius) var(--border-radius) 0;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-heading);
    line-height: 1.9;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  /* Concept grid (includeTools vs excludeTools) */
  .concept-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
  }

  .concept-card {
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    transition: border-color var(--transition);
  }

  .concept-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .concept-tag {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: var(--space-1) var(--space-3);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .concept-title {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .concept-title code {
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.95em;
    padding: 0.1em 0.4em;
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-tag-text);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .concept-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .concept-desc code {
    padding: 0.1em 0.4em;
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-tag-text);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  /* Permission list */
  .permission-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-2);
  }

  .permission-item {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
  }

  .permission-item--on {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .permission-item--off {
    border-color: var(--color-border);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    opacity: 0.7;
  }

  .permission-icon {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 1.75rem;
    height: 1.75rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .permission-item--on .permission-icon {
